# Auto-detect text files; force LF line endings in BOTH the repo AND the
# working tree (overrides core.autocrlf=true on Windows).
#
# Why LF everywhere instead of CRLF on Windows checkout:
#   Cursor/VSCode default to LF on save. With core.autocrlf=true, git
#   expects CRLF in the working tree on Windows, so every file Cursor
#   touched showed up as "modified" (LF will be replaced by CRLF). Forcing
#   LF in the working tree aligns git with what the editor actually writes,
#   eliminating the noise. The Windows-specific entries below (.bat / .ps1
#   / .cmd) explicitly request CRLF and remain unaffected.
* text=auto eol=lf

# Treat known-binary files explicitly so git never tries to normalise them.
# Without these rules `* text=auto` relies on git's content heuristic; the
# explicit list documents intent and protects large files (e.g. EasyOCR
# model weights ~100 MB) from any accidental mangling.
*.png    binary
*.jpg    binary
*.jpeg   binary
*.gif    binary
*.ico    binary
*.pdf    binary
*.zip    binary
*.exe    binary
*.dll    binary
*.pdb    binary
*.pth    binary
*.umd.min.js binary

# Windows-specific scripts force CRLF so Notepad / cmd.exe behave.
*.bat    text eol=crlf
*.cmd    text eol=crlf
*.ps1    text eol=crlf

# Shell scripts force LF (they need it to run on linux / WSL / docker).
*.sh     text eol=lf
